MEDIUM|internal/fanout/reviewdir.go:285|backupExisting() does os.RemoveAll(backup) then os.Rename(path, backup); BackupToDotBak() does os.RemoveAll(bak) then copyTree. If the rename/copy fails (cross-filesystem EXDEV when --output-dir and its .bak sibling are on different mounts, disk-full mid-copy, or SIGKILL), the single prior backup generation is already destroyed while the new backup is absent or partial. The live/original tree is preserved (good), but the one recoverable prior .bak is lost for no benefit — counter to the safe-to-retry goal.|Stage the new backup first: copy/rename into <path>.bak.new (or rename old .bak aside to .bak.old), confirm it is complete, then swap and only then remove the old generation. For backupExisting, attempt os.Rename before RemoveAll so a failed rename leaves the old .bak intact; detect EXDEV and fall back to copy+remove. Add a fault-injection test asserting the prior .bak survives a failed swap.|error-handling|120|internal/fanout/reviewdir.go:283-292 and internal/atomicfs/atomic.go:57-79|claude
MEDIUM|internal/fanout/review.go:217|validation.FilePath() — the system-directory reject (/etc, /proc, /sys) — runs only in the CLI flag parser outputDirFromFlags (review.go:76), NOT inside the exported PrepareReview. PrepareReview is public API reachable by the MCP handler and direct/test callers. A caller that sets req.OutputDir to a system path with Force=true reaches validateOutputDirRoot (only checks ReviewsRoot containment) then forceBackupOutputDir, which performs a destructive os.Rename before any system-path validation. Not exploitable today (MCP handler never sets OutputDir/Force) but a defense-in-depth gap in the engine.|Move the validation.FilePath(abs) check into PrepareReview in the req.OutputDir != \"\" branch, before forceBackupOutputDir, so the system-path reject is enforced for every caller, not only the CLI. Keep the CLI check too. Add an engine-level test passing a /etc output dir with Force=true and asserting rejection before any backup.|security|30|cmd/atcr/review.go:72-78 vs internal/fanout/review.go:213-227|claude
MEDIUM|internal/verify/emit_verification.go:144|WriteVerification() (BackupExistingVerification + atomicfs.WriteFileAtomic) has no non-test callers. Production verify writes verification.json via pipeline.go runVerify using writeGroupAtomic, calling BackupExistingVerification directly (pipeline.go:353). The AC5 backup IS exercised in production via that direct call, but every test that asserts backup behavior through WriteVerification validates a wrapper the app never runs — false confidence that the shipped path is covered.|Either delete the WriteVerification wrapper and drive backup tests through runVerify, or route runVerify through WriteVerification so the tested path equals the shipped path. At minimum, document WriteVerification as a test-only seam so a maintainer does not infer production backup coverage from its tests.|testing|60|internal/verify/emit_verification.go:144-167 and internal/verify/pipeline.go:349-358|claude
MEDIUM|internal/verify/pipeline.go:353|runVerify backs up only verification.json before overwriting it, but the same flush also re-writes findings.json and summary.json. The AC5 docstring (emit_verification.go:158-160) justifies the narrow scope by claiming findings.json/summary.json are already covered by reconciled.bak/ (AC4) — but reconciled.bak/ is written only by RunReconcile, not by runVerify. A standalone re-verify (atcr verify --fresh on an already-reconciled review, no reconcile re-run in the same command) overwrites findings.json/summary.json with no backup of their prior verified state.|Confirm whether atcr verify --fresh can run without a preceding RunReconcile in the same invocation. If yes, the AC4-covers-it claim is false: either back up findings.json/summary.json in runVerify too, or document the backup scope as verification.json-only and instruct users to re-run reconcile to snapshot the rest. Add a test for the standalone-verify overwrite path.|error-handling|120|internal/verify/pipeline.go:341-358 and internal/verify/emit_verification.go:155-167|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/reviewdir.go:356|guardForeignBackup relies on looksLikeReviewTree to decide a <output-dir>.bak is a genuine atcr backup safe to RemoveAll, but the marker is structural-name-only: any directory containing payload/, sources/, and reconciled/ subdirs is classified as atcr-owned and silently destroyed by the subsequent backupExisting. The whole never-destroy-user-data guard hinges on three generic directory names with no atcr provenance signature.|Tighten the marker: additionally require manifest.json at the backup root (every scaffolded review writes one), or write a hidden .atcr-backup sentinel in backupExisting and check for it. Add a test creating a foreign dir with payload/sources/reconciled and asserting --force refuses to destroy it.|security|30|internal/fanout/reviewdir.go:333-364|claude
LOW|internal/atomicfs/atomic.go:35|WriteFileAtomic renames a sibling temp file over path but never fsyncs the temp file before close nor fsyncs the parent dir after rename. Atomic rename prevents a concurrent reader from seeing a partial write, but across a power-loss/crash the rename can be durable while the data is not, yielding a zero-length or truncated file readers treat as valid. The docstring promise covers in-process partial-write safety, not crash durability — worth making explicit either way.|Add tmp.Sync() before tmp.Close(), and fsync the parent directory after os.Rename, for the durability-sensitive callers; or document that power-loss durability is out of scope for review artifacts. Lowest-risk: document, since artifacts are regenerable.|error-handling|60|internal/atomicfs/atomic.go:16-36|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/review.go:241|atcr review --force with a derived id (no --id, no --output-dir) lands in the default claimReviewDir branch, which never consults req.Force, so --force is a silent no-op. The struct comment documents this, but the CLI accepts the combination without any signal; an operator expecting --force to overwrite the last review gets a fresh auto-suffixed directory and no indication the flag did nothing.|Emit a one-line stderr notice when --force is set but the path is derived (no --id/--output-dir override), e.g. \"--force has no effect without --id or --output-dir; a new review directory was created\". No behavior change needed beyond the notice.|maintainability|15|internal/fanout/review.go:241-246|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/reviewdir.go:304|forceBackupReviewDir and forceBackupOutputDir compute the backup path via backupExisting but discard it (_, err := backupExisting(dir)). After a --force overwrite the user is never told where the prior tree went (<dir>.bak). On a destructive op the missing breadcrumb means a user who --forced by mistake has no pointer to the recoverable backup in the command output.|Have forceBackupReviewDir/forceBackupOutputDir return the backup path (already computed) and emit a stderr notice from PrepareReview/CLI when a non-empty target was actually backed up, e.g. \"backed up prior review to <dir>.bak\".|maintainability|30|internal/fanout/reviewdir.go:294-306 and :308-331|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/gate.go:188|If BackupToDotBak(reconDir) fails (disk full while copying the tree, or a permission error on reconciled.bak), RunReconcile returns an error and emits nothing — the re-reconcile is aborted even though the live reconciled/ is untouched and a re-emit would have succeeded. A backup is a safety convenience; hard-blocking the primary operation on it inverts the priority, and a partial reconciled.bak (RemoveAll ran, copyTree failed partway) is left behind looking like a valid recovery point.|Consider degrading a backup failure to a logged warning and continuing the re-emit, OR document backup as a hard precondition. Either way, clean up the partial reconciled.bak on copy failure so a stale half-backup is not mistaken for a valid generation.|error-handling|30|internal/reconcile/gate.go:187-191 and internal/atomicfs/atomic.go:66-77|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/gate.go:187|The Epic 4.7 backup runs before the adjudication validation block (gate.go:193-230). On a pure adjudication re-invocation that fails validation (baseline-hash mismatch at :222-224, unknown cluster id, etc.), RunReconcile pays a full-tree copy of reconciled/ and then errors out, leaving a reconciled.bak/ that is a copy of state never changed — a misleading recovery point for an operation that did nothing.|Move the BackupToDotBak call to just before Emit (gate.go:245), after adjudication validation succeeds, so the backup is taken only when an actual overwrite is imminent. This also narrows the un-cancellable copy window the docstring's between-stages ctx-check contract implies.|maintainability|30|internal/reconcile/gate.go:187-247|claude

